VIRTUAL MACHINE TESTS
=====================

VM Tests boot a QEMU guest against a selected Linux kernel and run OBI's
integration and BPF-verifier test suites inside it. This allows OBI to be
exercised against a matrix of kernel versions and architectures.

The host's OBI source tree is shared into the guest via 9p (mount tag 'obi'),
overlaid with /overlay/upper, and mounted at /build. Test outputs flow back
through a second 9p mount (mount tag 'testout') so artifacts are available on
the host after the VM exits. LVH-sourced kernels also receive their loadable
modules through a third 9p mount (tag 'modules').


KERNEL MATRIX
=============

All kernels are described in 'kernels.yaml'. Each entry declares:

  - id:              short slug used as KERNEL_ID and in artifact filenames
  - lvh_tag:         exact tag on quay.io/lvh-images/kernel-images, pinned to
                     a dated build (e.g. "6.12-20260504.013701")
  - pr_integration:  true => included in the PR-default integration matrix
  - pr_verifier:     true => included in the PR-default verifier matrix

Everything runs on amd64. arm64 was dropped because GitHub-hosted arm64
runners don't expose nested KVM and TCG is ~12x slower — infeasible at
PR scale.

Steady state:
  - 5.10-lts, 5.15-lts, 6.1-lts, 6.6-lts, 6.12-lts, 6.18-lts   LTS
  - bpf, bpf-next                                               Dev trees
  - rhel8.9, rhel8.10, rhel9.6                                  RHEL

PR runs cover only the fast-lane integration kernels (5.15-lts + 6.18-lts).
To include a kernel in PR runs, set 'pr_integration: true' (or
'pr_verifier: true') on its kernels.yaml entry.


KERNEL ARTIFACTS
================

Kernels are not committed to the repository. They are pulled on demand from
'quay.io/lvh-images/kernel-images:<lvh_tag>' and cached under:

    internal/test/vm/lvh/out/vmlinuz-${id}-${arch}
    internal/test/vm/lvh/out/vmlinuz-${id}-${arch}.config
    internal/test/vm/lvh/out/vmlinuz-${id}-${arch}.buildinfo
    internal/test/vm/lvh/out/modules-${id}-${arch}/<release>/

Each OCI artifact ships vmlinuz + .config + /lib/modules/<release> with all
.ko files. The build pipeline used to produce these images is maintained by
the Cilium project at github.com/cilium/little-vm-helper-images.

To bump a kernel:

  1. Find the desired tag at
     https://quay.io/repository/lvh-images/kernel-images?tab=tags
     (always prefer dated tags over the rolling '<id>-main' alias).
  2. Update 'lvh_tag' in 'kernels.yaml'.
  3. Done. CI re-pulls on the next run.


USAGE
=====

Run integration tests inside the VM against a specific kernel:

    KERNEL_ID=6.18-lts make

Run the BPF verifier suite instead of integration tests:

    TARGET_TEST=run-bpf-verifier-vm KERNEL_ID=6.12-lts make

Boot with an explicit kernel path (overrides KERNEL_ID):

    KERNEL=/tmp/bzImage MODULES_DIR=/tmp/modules make

Drop into an interactive shell instead of running tests:

    TARGET_TEST= KERNEL_ID=6.18-lts make

For interactive debugging, the qemu serial console (-nographic) attaches to
your terminal; an agetty respawn auto-logs in as root on ttyS0.


PULLING KERNELS LOCALLY
=======================

'lvh/pull-kernel.sh' fetches a single kernel from quay and extracts vmlinuz
plus the modules tree:

    bash internal/test/vm/lvh/pull-kernel.sh 6.12-lts amd64

'prepare-kernel.sh' wraps the pull for the Makefile and CI; it returns
'KERNEL=' and 'MODULES_DIR=' assignments for eval and pulls on cache miss:

    eval "$(bash internal/test/vm/prepare-kernel.sh 6.12-lts amd64)"


CI WORKFLOWS
============

  - workflow_integration_tests_vm.yml
        Runs integration tests inside the VM for every kernel marked
        'pr_integration: true' in kernels.yaml.

  - pull_request.yml :: bpf-verifier
        Runs BPF verifier tests inside the VM for every kernel marked
        'pr_verifier: true'. Cheap (~5 minutes per kernel on amd64 KVM).


TECHNICAL NOTES
===============

  - Rootfs definition lives in 'Dockerfile' in this directory. The Alpine
    image ships docker, docker-cli-buildx, docker-cli-compose, iptables
    (legacy + nft), openrc, plus a Go toolchain imported from the pinned
    golang image. No sshd — debug via the serial console (-nographic).
  - 'modules-load' openrc service mounts /lib/modules via 9p (if a 'modules'
    mount tag is supplied) and modprobes overlay/br_netfilter/iptable_*/
    nf_*/veth/vxlan/macvlan before localmount runs. This is required for
    LVH kernels (modular) and is a harmless no-op for monolithic ones.
  - /sbin/iptables is symlinked to iptables-legacy at image build time.
    All LVH kernels enable CONFIG_IP_NF_IPTABLES_LEGACY but disable
    CONFIG_NFT_NAT/COMPAT, so the nft backend fails on "TABLE_ADD nat" and
    legacy is the only one Docker can use.
  - 'GOCACHE' and 'TMPDIR' are pointed at /build (overlay over qcow2 ~20GB)
    rather than tmpfs /tmp, so heavy Go builds (verifier test pulls k8s.io
    deps) don't OOM the 8GB-RAM tmpfs.
